<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-12-18T10:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-12-18T10:45:00-05:00" n="365" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d365">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/2748: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Jefferson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-12-18T10:00:00-05:45"><hi rend="italic">December
                                            18, 1920—10 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 10:12
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>66. Department’s December 15, 6 p.m. President Chamorro agreed to
                                exchange of notes regarding election law expert and stated that his
                                note would make clear that new law would not be retroactive but
                                applies to future elections. Will telegraph Department upon receipt
                                of note.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Jefferson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>